# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cavity-resonators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] A **dielectric resonator** is a piece of dielectric (nonconductive but polarizable) material, usually ceramic, that is designed to function as a resonator for radio waves, generally in the microwave and millimeter wave bands.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] The microwaves are confined inside the resonator material by the abrupt change in permittivity at the surface, and bounce back and forth between the sides.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] At certain frequencies, the resonant frequencies, the microwaves form standing waves in the resonator, oscillating with large amplitudes.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Dielectric resonators generally consist of a "puck" of ceramic that has a large dielectric constant and a low dissipation factor.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] The resonant frequency is determined by the overall physical dimensions of the resonator and the dielectric constant of the material.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Dielectric resonators function similarly to cavity resonators, hollow metal boxes that are also widely used as resonators at microwave frequencies, except that the radio waves are reflected by the large change in permittivity rather than by the conductivity of the metal.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] At millimeter wave frequencies, metal surfaces become lossy reflectors, so dielectric resonators are used at these frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Dielectric resonators' main use is in millimeter-wave electronic oscillators (**dielectric resonator oscillator**, **DRO**) to control the frequency of the radio waves generated.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] They are also used as bandpass filters as well as antennas.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] In the late 19th century, Lord Rayleigh demonstrated that an infinitely long cylindrical rod made up of dielectric material could serve as a waveguide.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Additional theoretical and experimental work done in Germany in early 20th century, offered further insight into the behavior of electromagnetic waves in dielectric rod waveguides.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Since a dielectric resonator can be thought of as a truncated dielectric rod waveguide, this research was essential for scientific understanding of electromagnetic phenomena in dielectric resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Richtmyer published a study in which he showed that dielectric structures can act just as metallic cavity resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] He appropriately named these structures *dielectric resonators*.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Richtmyer also demonstrated that, if exposed to free space, dielectric resonators must radiate because of the boundary conditions at the dielectric-to-air interface.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] These results were later used in the development of DRA (Dielectric Resonator Antenna).
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Due to World War II, lack of advanced materials and adequate manufacturing techniques, dielectric resonators fell in relative obscurity for another two decades after Richtmyer's study was published.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] However, in the 1960s, as high-frequency electronics and modern communications industry started to take off, dielectric resonators gained in significance.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] They offered a size-reducing design alternative to bulky waveguide filters and lower-cost alternatives for electronic oscillator, frequency selective limiter and slow-wave circuits.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] In addition to cost and size, other advantages that dielectric resonators have over conventional metal cavity resonators are lower weight, material availability, and ease of manufacturing.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] There is a vast availability of different dielectric resonators on the market today with unloaded Q factor on the order of 10000s.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Even so, electric and magnetic fields decay from their maximum values considerably when they are away from the resonator walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Most of the energy is stored in the resonator at a given resonant frequency for a sufficiently high dielectric constant $\varepsilon _{r}$ .
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Dielectric resonators can exhibit an extremely high Q factor that is comparable to a metal walled cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] There are three types of resonant modes that can be excited in dielectric resonators: transverse electric (TE), transverse magnetic (TM) or hybrid electromagnetic (HEM) modes.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Theoretically, there is an infinite number of modes in each of the three groups, and desired mode is usually selected based on the application requirements.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Generally, $TE_{01n}$ mode is used in most non-radiating applications, but other modes can have certain advantages for specific applications.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Where a is the radius of the cylindrical resonator and L is its length.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Resonant frequency $f_{GHz}$ is in gigahertz.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] However, since a dielectric resonator is usually enclosed in a conducting cavity for most applications, the real resonant frequencies are different from the one calculated above.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] As conducting walls of the enclosing cavity approach the resonator, change in boundary conditions and field containment start to affect resonant frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] The size and type of the material encapsulating the cavity can drastically impact the performance of the resonant circuit.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] This phenomenon can be explained using cavity perturbation theory.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] The most common problem exhibited by dielectric resonator circuits is their sensitivity to temperature variation and mechanical vibrations.
[src:cavity-resonators/dielectric-resonator] Even though recent improvements in materials science and manufacturing mitigated some of these issues, compensating techniques still may be required to stabilize the circuit performance over temperature and frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] A **helical resonator** is a passive electrical component that can be used as a filter resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Physically, a helical resonator is a wire helix surrounded by a square or cylindrical conductive shield.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] One end of the helix is connected to the shield and the other end is left open (Weston, 2001, p.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] The device works like a coaxial resonator, but it is much shorter because the helical inner conductor reduces the velocity of wave propagation (Lancaster, 2006, p.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Like cavity resonators, helical resonators can achieve Q factors in the 1000s.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] This is because at high frequencies, the skin effect results in most of the current flowing on the surface of the helix and shield.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Plating the shield walls and helix with high conductivity materials increases the Q beyond that of bare copper (Blattenberger, 1989).
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] The length of wire is one quarter of the wavelength of interest.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] The helix is space wound, the gap between turns is equal to the diameter of the wire (Blattenberger, 1989).
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] If the open end of the helix is close to the end cap of the metal shield the length is somewhat reduced due to the capacitance between the conductor and the shield (Whittaker, 2000, p.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Coupling to the resonator can be achieved with a tap wire soldered to the helix at some distance from the shorted end.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Input impedance varies with distance from the shorted end by impedance transformer action.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] The tap point is chosen to achieve an impedance match with the connected circuit.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Tuning of the resonator may be achieved by inserting a screw into the central axis of the helix (Weston, 2001, p.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Other means of input and output coupling used are a wire loop coupling to the magnetic field near the shorted end, or a probe capacitively coupling near the open end.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Coupling between resonators in a multi-resonator filter is often simply achieved with apertures in the shielding between them (Whittaker, 2000, p.
[src:cavity-resonators/helical-resonator] Helical resonators are well suited to UHF frequencies ranging from 600 MHz to 1500 MHz (Blattenberger, 1989).
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] A **microwave cavity** or **radio frequency cavity** (**RF cavity**) is a special type of resonator, consisting of a closed (or largely closed) metal structure that confines electromagnetic fields in the microwave or RF region of the spectrum.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The structure is either hollow or filled with dielectric material.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The microwaves bounce back and forth between the walls of the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] At the cavity's resonant frequencies they reinforce to form standing waves in the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Therefore, the cavity functions similarly to an organ pipe or sound box in a musical instrument, oscillating preferentially at a series of frequencies, its resonant frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Thus it can act as a bandpass filter, allowing microwaves of a particular frequency to pass while blocking microwaves at nearby frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] A microwave cavity acts similarly to a resonant circuit with extremely low loss at its frequency of operation, resulting in quality factors (Q factors) up to the order of 106, for copper cavities, compared to 102 for circuits made with separate inductors and capacitors at the same frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For superconducting cavities, quality factors up to the order of 1010 are possible.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] They are used in place of resonant circuits at microwave frequencies, since at these frequencies discrete resonant circuits cannot be built because the values of inductance and capacitance needed are too low.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] RF cavities can also manipulate charged particles passing through them by application of acceleration voltage and are thus used in particle accelerators and microwave vacuum tubes such as klystrons and magnetrons.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Most resonant cavities are made from closed (or short-circuited) sections of waveguide or high-permittivity dielectric material (see dielectric resonator).
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Electric and magnetic energy is stored in the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] This energy decays over time due to several possible loss mechanisms.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Basic losses are due to finite conductivity of cavity walls and dielectric losses of material filling the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Other loss mechanisms exist in evacuated cavities, for example the multipactor effect or field electron emission.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Both multipactor effect and field electron emission generate copious electrons inside the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] These electrons are accelerated by the electric field in the cavity and thus extract energy from the stored energy of the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Eventually the electrons strike the walls of the cavity and lose their energy.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] In superconducting radio frequency cavities there are additional energy loss mechanisms associated with the deterioration of the electric conductivity of the superconducting surface due to heating or contamination.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Every cavity has numerous resonant frequencies that correspond to electromagnetic field modes satisfying necessary boundary conditions on the walls of the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Because of these boundary conditions that must be satisfied at resonance (tangential electric fields must be zero at cavity walls), at resonance, cavity dimensions must satisfy particular values.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Depending on the resonance transverse mode, transverse cavity dimensions may be constrained to expressions related to geometric functions, or to zeros of Bessel functions or their derivatives (see below), depending on the symmetry properties of the cavity's shape.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Alternately it follows that cavity length must be an integer multiple of half-wavelength at resonance (see page 451 of Ramo et al).
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] In this case, a resonant cavity can be thought of as a resonance in a short circuited half-wavelength transmission line.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The external dimensions of a cavity can be made considerably smaller at its lowest frequency mode by loading the cavity with either capacitive or inductive elements.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Loaded cavities usually have lower symmetries and compromise certain performance indicators, such as the best Q factor.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] As examples, the reentrant cavity and helical resonator are capacitive and inductive loaded cavities, respectively.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Single-cell cavities can be combined in a structure to accelerate particles (such as electrons or ions) more efficiently than a string of independent single cell cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Department of Energy shows a multi-cell superconducting cavity in a clean room at Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] A microwave cavity has a fundamental mode, which exhibits the lowest resonant frequency of all possible resonant modes.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For example, the fundamental mode of a cylindrical cavity is the TM010 mode.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For certain applications, there is motivation to reduce the dimensions of the cavity.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] This can be done by using a loaded cavity, where a capacitive or an inductive load is integrated in the cavity's structure.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The precise resonant frequency of a loaded cavity must be calculated using finite element methods for Maxwell's equations with boundary conditions.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Loaded cavities (or resonators) can also be configured as multi-cell cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Loaded cavities are particularly suited for accelerating low velocity charged particles.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] This application for many types of loaded cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The Q factor of a particular mode in a resonant cavity can be calculated.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For a cavity with high degrees of symmetry, using analytical expressions of the electric and magnetic field, surface currents in the conducting walls and electric field in dielectric lossy material.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For cavities with arbitrary shapes, finite element methods for Maxwell's equations with boundary conditions must be used.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Measurement of the Q of a cavity are done using a Vector Network analyzer (electrical), or in the case of a very high Q by measuring the exponential decay time $\tau$ of the fields, and using the relationship $Q=\pi f\tau$ .
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The electromagnetic fields in the cavity are excited via external coupling.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] An external power source is usually coupled to the cavity by a small aperture, a small wire probe or a loop, see page 563 of Ramo et al.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] External coupling structure has an effect on cavity performance and needs to be considered in the overall analysis, see Montgomery et al page 232.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The resonant frequencies of a cavity are a function of its geometry.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Resonance frequencies of a rectangular microwave cavity for any $\scriptstyle TE_{mnl}$ or $\scriptstyle TM_{mnl}$ resonant mode can be found by imposing boundary conditions on electromagnetic field expressions.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The field solutions of a cylindrical cavity of length $\scriptstyle L$ and radius $\scriptstyle R$ follow from the solutions of a cylindrical waveguide with additional electric boundary conditions at the position of the enclosing plates.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The resonance frequencies are different for TE and TM modes.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The quality factor $\scriptstyle Q$ of a cavity can be decomposed into three parts, representing different power loss mechanisms.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] where $\scriptstyle \eta$ is the intrinsic impedance of the dielectric, $\scriptstyle R_{s}$ is the surface resistivity of the cavity walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Microwave resonant cavities can be represented and thought of as simple LC circuits, see Montgomery et al pages 207-239.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] For a microwave cavity, the stored electric energy is equal to the stored magnetic energy at resonance as is the case for a resonant LC circuit.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] where V is the cavity volume, $\scriptstyle k_{mnl}$ is the mode wavenumber and $\scriptstyle \epsilon$ and $\scriptstyle \mu$ are permittivity and permeability respectively.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] To better understand the utility of resonant cavities at microwave frequencies, it is useful to note that conventional inductors and capacitors start to become impractically small with frequency in the VHF, and definitely so for frequencies above one gigahertz.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Because of their low losses and high Q factors, cavity resonators are preferred over conventional LC and transmission-line resonators at high frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Conventional inductors are usually wound from wire in the shape of a helix with no core.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Skin effect causes the high frequency resistance of inductors to be many times their direct current resistance.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] In addition, capacitance between turns causes dielectric losses in the insulation which coats the wires.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] These effects make the high frequency resistance greater and decrease the Q factor.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Conventional capacitors use air, mica, ceramic or perhaps teflon for a dielectric.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Even with a low loss dielectric, capacitors are also subject to skin effect losses in their leads and plates.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Both effects increase their equivalent series resistance and reduce their Q.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Even if the Q factor of VHF inductors and capacitors is high enough to be useful, their parasitic properties can significantly affect their performance in this frequency range.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The shunt capacitance of an inductor may be more significant than its desirable series inductance.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The series inductance of a capacitor may be more significant than its desirable shunt capacitance.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] As a result, in the VHF or microwave regions, a capacitor may appear to be an inductor and an inductor may appear to be a capacitor.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] These phenomena are better known as parasitic inductance and parasitic capacitance.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Dielectric loss of air is extremely low for high-frequency electric or magnetic fields.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Air-filled microwave cavities confine electric and magnetic fields to the air spaces between their walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Electric losses in such cavities are almost exclusively due to currents flowing in cavity walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] While losses from wall currents are small, cavities are frequently plated with silver to increase their electrical conductivity and reduce these losses even further.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Copper cavities frequently oxidize, which increases their loss.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Silver or gold plating prevents oxidation and reduces electrical losses in cavity walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Even though gold is not quite as good a conductor as copper, it still prevents oxidation and the resulting deterioration of Q factor over time.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] However, because of its high cost, it is used only in the most demanding applications.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] Some satellite resonators are silver-plated and covered with a gold flash layer.
[src:cavity-resonators/microwave-cavity] The current then mostly flows in the high-conductivity silver layer, while the gold flash layer protects the silver layer from oxidizing.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In physics and engineering, the **quality factor** or **Q factor** is a dimensionless parameter that describes how underdamped an oscillator or resonator is.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Resonators with high quality factors have low damping, so that they ring or vibrate longer.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For example, a pendulum suspended from a precision bearing, oscillating in air, has a high Q, while a pendulum immersed in oil has a low one.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] There are two definitions of Q that give numerically similar, but not identical, results.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The more general definition is the ratio of the initial energy stored in the resonator to the energy lost in one radian of the cycle of oscillation.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] An alternative definition of Q factor, more applicable to high Q oscillators, is as the ratio of a resonator's centre frequency to its bandwidth when subject to an oscillating driving force.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q factor is a parameter that describes the resonance behavior of a damped harmonic oscillator (resonator).
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Sinusoidally driven resonators having higher Q factors resonate with greater amplitudes (at the resonant frequency) but have a smaller range of frequencies around that frequency for which they resonate; the range of frequencies for which the oscillator resonates is called the bandwidth.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Thus, a high-Q tuned circuit in a radio receiver would be more difficult to tune, but would have more selectivity; it would do a better job of filtering out signals from other stations that lie nearby on the spectrum.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] High-Q oscillators oscillate with a smaller range of frequencies and are more stable.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The quality factor of devices varies substantially from system to system, depending on their function and design.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Systems for which damping is important (such as dampers keeping a door from slamming shut) have Q near 1⁄2.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Clocks, lasers, and other resonating systems that need either strong resonance or high frequency stability have high quality factors.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Tuning forks have quality factors around 1000.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The quality factor of atomic clocks, superconducting RF cavities used in accelerators, and some high-Q lasers can reach 1011 and higher.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] There are many alternative quantities used by physicists and engineers to describe how damped an oscillator is.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Important examples include: the damping ratio, relative bandwidth, linewidth and bandwidth measured in octaves.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Johnson of Western Electric Company's Engineering Department while evaluating the quality of coils (inductors).
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] His choice of the symbol Q was only because, at the time, all other letters of the alphabet were taken.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The term was not intended as an abbreviation for "quality" or "quality factor", although these terms have grown to be associated with it.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The definition of Q since its first use in 1914 has been generalized to apply to coils and condensers, resonant circuits, resonant devices, resonant transmission lines, cavity resonators,.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] It has expanded beyond the electronics field to apply to dynamical systems in general: mechanical and acoustic resonators, material Q and quantum systems such as spectral lines and particle resonances, and optical resonators such as laser cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] There are two common definitions for Q, which apply generally to all these systems but are not exactly equivalent.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] They become approximately equivalent as Q becomes larger, meaning the resonator becomes less damped.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Under this definition, Q is the reciprocal of fractional bandwidth.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The factor 2*π* makes Q expressible in simpler terms, involving only the coefficients of the second-order differential equation describing most resonant systems, electrical or mechanical.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In electrical systems, the stored energy is the sum of energies stored in lossless inductors and capacitors; the lost energy is the sum of the energies dissipated in resistors per cycle.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In mechanical systems, the stored energy is the sum of the potential and kinetic energies at some point in time; the lost energy is the work done by an external force, per cycle, to maintain amplitude.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] where ω is the angular frequency at which the stored energy and power loss are measured.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] This definition is consistent with its usage in describing circuits with a single reactive element (capacitor or inductor), where it can be shown to be equal to the ratio of reactive power to real power.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q-factor determines the qualitative behavior of simple damped oscillators.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Starting from the stored energy definition, it can be shown that $Q={\frac {1}{2\zeta }}$ , where $\zeta$ is the damping ratio.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In negative feedback systems, the dominant closed-loop response is often well-modeled by a second-order system.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The phase margin of the open-loop system sets the quality factor Q of the closed-loop system; as the phase margin decreases, the approximate second-order closed-loop system is made more oscillatory (i.e., has a higher quality factor).
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Physically speaking, Q is approximately the ratio of the stored energy to the energy dissipated over one radian of the oscillation; or nearly equivalently, at high enough Q values, 2π times the ratio of the total energy stored and the energy lost in a single cycle.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] It is a dimensionless parameter that compares the exponential time constant τ for decay of an oscillating physical system's amplitude to its oscillation period.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Equivalently, it compares the frequency at which a system oscillates to the rate at which it dissipates its energy.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] More precisely, the frequency and period used should be based on the system's natural frequency, which at low Q values is somewhat higher than the oscillation frequency as measured by zero crossings.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Equivalently (for large values of Q), the Q factor is approximately the number of oscillations required for a freely oscillating system's energy to fall off to *e*−2*π*, or about 1⁄535 or 0.2%, of its original energy.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] This means the amplitude falls off to approximately *e*−*π* or 4% of its original amplitude.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The width (bandwidth) of the resonance is given by (approximately): $\Delta f={\frac {f_{\mathrm {N} }}{Q}},\,$ where *f*N is the natural frequency, and Δ*f*, the bandwidth, is the width of the range of frequencies for which the energy is at least half its peak value.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The energy of oscillation, or the power dissipation, decays twice as fast, that is, as the square of the amplitude, as *e*−2*αt* or *e*−2*t/τ*.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For this system, when *Q* > ⁠1/2⁠ (i.e., when the system is underdamped), it has two complex conjugate poles that each have a real part of −α.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] That is, the attenuation parameter α represents the rate of exponential decay of the oscillations (that is, of the output after an impulse) into the system.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] A higher quality factor implies a lower attenuation rate, and so high-Q systems oscillate for many cycles.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For example, high-quality bells have an approximately pure sinusoidal tone for a long time after being struck by a hammer.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For an electrically resonant system, the *Q* factor represents the effect of electrical resistance and, for electromechanical resonators such as quartz crystals, mechanical friction.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The 2-sided bandwidth relative to a resonant frequency of *F*0 (Hz) is ${\frac {F_{0}}{Q}}$ .
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For example, an antenna tuned to have a Q value of 10 and a centre frequency of 100 kHz would have a 3 dB bandwidth of 10 kHz.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In audio, bandwidth is often expressed in terms of octaves.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] where R, L, and C are the resistance, inductance and capacitance of the tuned circuit, respectively.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Larger series resistances correspond to lower circuit Q values.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Consider a circuit where R, L, and C are all in parallel.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The lower the parallel resistance is, the more effect it will have in damping the circuit and thus result in lower Q.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] This is useful in filter design to determine the bandwidth.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In a parallel LC circuit where the main loss is the resistance of the inductor, R, in series with the inductance, L, Q is as in the series circuit.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] This is a common circumstance for resonators, where limiting the resistance of the inductor to improve Q and narrow the bandwidth is the desired result.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q of an individual reactive component depends on the frequency at which it is evaluated, which is typically the resonant frequency of the circuit that it is used in.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q of an inductor with a series loss resistance is the Q of a resonant circuit using that inductor (including its series loss) and a perfect capacitor.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For a single damped mass-spring system, the Q factor represents the effect of simplified viscous damping or drag, where the damping force or drag force is proportional to velocity.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The formula for the Q factor is: $Q={\frac {\sqrt {Mk}}{D}},\,$ where M is the mass, k is the spring constant, and D is the damping coefficient, defined by the equation *F*damping = −*Dv*, where v is the velocity.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q of a musical instrument is critical; an excessively high Q in a resonator will not evenly amplify the multiple frequencies an instrument produces.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] For this reason, string instruments often have bodies with complex shapes, so that they produce a wide range of frequencies fairly evenly.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The Q of a brass instrument or wind instrument needs to be high enough to pick one frequency out of the broader-spectrum buzzing of the lips or reed.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] By contrast, a vuvuzela is made of flexible plastic, and therefore has a very low Q for a brass instrument, giving it a muddy, breathy tone.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Instruments made of stiffer plastic, brass, or wood have higher Q values.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] An excessively high Q can make it harder to hit a note.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Q in an instrument may vary across frequencies, but this may not be desirable.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Helmholtz resonators have a very high Q, as they are designed for picking out a very narrow range of frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] In optics, the Q factor of a resonant cavity is given by $Q={\frac {2\pi f_{o}\,E}{P}},\,$ where fo is the resonant frequency, E is the stored energy in the cavity, and *P* = −⁠*dE*/*dt*⁠ is the power dissipated.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The optical Q is equal to the ratio of the resonant frequency to the bandwidth of the cavity resonance.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] The average lifetime of a resonant photon in the cavity is proportional to the cavity's Q.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] If the Q factor of a laser's cavity is abruptly changed from a low value to a high one, the laser will emit a pulse of light that is much more intense than the laser's normal continuous output.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] Q factor is of particular importance in plasmonics, where loss is linked to the damping of the surface plasmon resonance.
[src:cavity-resonators/q-factor] While loss is normally considered a hindrance in the development of plasmonic devices, it is possible to leverage this property to present new enhanced functionalities.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A **resonator** is a device or system that exhibits resonance or resonant behavior.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] That is, it naturally oscillates with greater amplitude at some frequencies, called resonant frequencies, than at other frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The oscillations in a resonator can be either electromagnetic or mechanical (including acoustic).
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Resonators are used to either generate waves of specific frequencies or to select specific frequencies from a signal.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Musical instruments use acoustic resonators that produce sound waves of specific tones.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Another example is quartz crystals used in electronic devices such as radio transmitters and quartz watches to produce oscillations of very precise frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A **cavity resonator** is one in which waves exist in a hollow space inside the device.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In electronics and radio, microwave cavities consisting of hollow metal boxes are used in microwave transmitters, receivers and test equipment to control frequency, in place of the tuned circuits which are used at lower frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Acoustic cavity resonators, in which sound is produced by air vibrating in a cavity with one opening, are known as Helmholtz resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A physical system can have as many resonant frequencies as it has degrees of freedom; each degree of freedom can vibrate as a harmonic oscillator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Systems with one degree of freedom, such as a mass on a spring, pendulums, balance wheels, and LC tuned circuits have one resonant frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Systems with two degrees of freedom, such as coupled pendulums and resonant transformers can have two resonant frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A crystal lattice composed of *N* atoms bound together can have *N* resonant frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] As the number of coupled harmonic oscillators grows, the time it takes to transfer energy from one to the next becomes significant.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The vibrations in them begin to travel through the coupled harmonic oscillators in waves, from one oscillator to the next.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The term *resonator* is most often used for a homogeneous object in which vibrations travel as waves, at an approximately constant velocity, bouncing back and forth between the sides of the resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The material of the resonator, through which the waves flow, can be viewed as being made of millions of coupled moving parts (such as atoms).
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Therefore, they can have millions of resonant frequencies, although only a few may be used in practical resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The oppositely moving waves interfere with each other, and at its resonant frequencies reinforce each other to create a pattern of standing waves in the resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] If the distance between the sides is $d\,$ , the length of a round trip is $2d\,$ .
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] To cause resonance, the phase of a sinusoidal wave after a round trip must be equal to the initial phase so the waves self-reinforce.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] So the resonant frequencies of resonators, called normal modes, are equally spaced multiples (harmonics) of a lowest frequency called the fundamental frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The above analysis assumes the medium inside the resonator is homogeneous, so the waves travel at a constant speed, and that the shape of the resonator is rectilinear.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] If the resonator is inhomogeneous or has a nonrectilinear shape, like a circular drumhead or a cylindrical microwave cavity, the resonant frequencies may not occur at equally spaced multiples of the fundamental frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] They are then called overtones instead of harmonics.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] There may be several such series of resonant frequencies in a single resonator, corresponding to different modes of vibration.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] An electrical circuit composed of discrete components can act as a resonator when both an inductor and capacitor are included.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Oscillations are limited by the inclusion of resistance, either via a specific resistor component, or due to resistance of the inductor windings.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Such resonant circuits are also called RLC circuits after the circuit symbols for the components.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A distributed-parameter resonator has capacitance, inductance, and resistance that cannot be isolated into separate lumped capacitors, inductors, or resistors.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] An example of this, much used in filtering, is the helical resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] An inductor consisting of a coil of wire, is self-resonant at a certain frequency due to the parasitic capacitance between its turns.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] This is often an unwanted effect that can cause parasitic oscillations in RF circuits.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The self-resonance of inductors is used in a few circuits, such as the Tesla coil.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A *cavity resonator* is a hollow closed conductor such as a metal box or a cavity within a metal block, containing electromagnetic waves (radio waves) reflecting back and forth between the cavity's walls.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] When a source of radio waves at one of the cavity's resonant frequencies is applied, the oppositely-moving waves form standing waves, and the cavity stores electromagnetic energy.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Since the cavity's lowest resonant frequency, the fundamental frequency, is that at which the width of the cavity is equal to a half-wavelength (λ/2), cavity resonators are only used at microwave frequencies and above, where wavelengths are short enough that the cavity is conveniently small in size.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Due to the low resistance of their conductive walls, cavity resonators have very high Q factors; that is their bandwidth, the range of frequencies around the resonant frequency at which they will resonate, is very narrow.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Thus they can act as narrow bandpass filters.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Cavity resonators are widely used as the frequency determining element in microwave oscillators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Their resonant frequency can be tuned by moving one of the walls of the cavity in or out, changing its size.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The cavity magnetron is a vacuum tube with a filament in the center of an evacuated, lobed, circular cavity resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A perpendicular magnetic field is imposed by a permanent magnet.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The magnetic field causes the electrons, attracted to the (relatively) positive outer part of the chamber, to spiral outward in a circular path rather than moving directly to this anode.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Spaced about the rim of the chamber are cylindrical cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The cavities are open along their length and so they connect with the common cavity space.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] As electrons sweep past these openings they induce a resonant high frequency radio field in the cavity, which in turn causes the electrons to bunch into groups.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A portion of this field is extracted with a short antenna that is connected to a waveguide (a metal tube usually of rectangular cross section).
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The waveguide directs the extracted RF energy to the load, which may be a cooking chamber in a microwave oven or a high gain antenna in the case of radar.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The klystron, tube waveguide, is a beam tube including at least two apertured cavity resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The beam of charged particles passes through the apertures of the resonators, often tunable wave reflection grids, in succession.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A collector electrode is provided to intercept the beam after passing through the resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The first resonator causes bunching of the particles passing through it.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The bunched particles travel in a field-free region where further bunching occurs, then the bunched particles enter the second resonator giving up their energy to excite it into oscillations.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] It is a particle accelerator that works in conjunction with a specifically tuned cavity by the configuration of the structures.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The reflex klystron is a klystron utilizing only a single apertured cavity resonator through which the beam of charged particles passes, first in one direction.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A repeller electrode is provided to repel (or redirect) the beam after passage through the resonator back through the resonator in the other direction and in proper phase to reinforce the oscillations set up in the resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] On the beamline of an accelerator system, there are specific sections that are cavity resonators for radio frequency (RF) radiation.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The (charged) particles that are to be accelerated pass through these cavities in such a way that the microwave electric field transfers energy to the particles, thus increasing their kinetic energy and thus accelerating them.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Several large accelerator facilities employ superconducting niobium cavities for improved performance compared to metallic (copper) cavities.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The loop-gap resonator (LGR) is made by cutting a narrow slit along the length of a conducting tube.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The slit has an effective capacitance and the bore of the resonator has an effective inductance.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Therefore, the LGR can be modeled as an RLC circuit and has a resonant frequency that is typically between 200 MHz and 2 GHz.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In the absence of radiation losses, the effective resistance of the LGR is determined by the resistivity and electromagnetic skin depth of the conductor used to make the resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] One key advantage of the LGR is that, at its resonant frequency, its dimensions are small compared to the free-space wavelength of the electromagnetic fields.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Therefore, it is possible to use LGRs to construct a compact and high-Q resonator that operates at relatively low frequencies where cavity resonators would be impractically large.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] If a piece of material with large dielectric constant is surrounded by a material with much lower dielectric constant, then this abrupt change in dielectric constant can cause confinement of an electromagnetic wave, which leads to a resonator that acts similarly to a cavity resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Transmission lines are structures that allow broadband transmission of electromagnetic waves, e.g. at radio or microwave frequencies.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Abrupt change of impedance (e.g. open or short) in a transmission line causes reflection of the transmitted signal.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Two such reflectors on a transmission line evoke standing waves between them and thus act as a one-dimensional resonator, with the resonance frequencies determined by their distance and the effective dielectric constant of the transmission line.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] A common form is the resonant stub, a length of transmission line terminated in either a short circuit or open circuit, connected in series or parallel with a main transmission line.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Planar transmission-line resonators are commonly employed for coplanar, stripline, and microstrip transmission lines.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Such planar transmission-line resonators can be very compact in size and are widely used elements in microwave circuitry.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In cryogenic solid-state research, superconducting transmission-line resonators contribute to solid-state spectroscopy and quantum information science.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In a laser, light is amplified in a cavity resonator that is usually composed of two or more mirrors.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Thus an *optical cavity*, also known as a resonator, is a cavity with walls that reflect electromagnetic waves (i.e. light).
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] This allows standing wave modes to exist with little loss.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Mechanical resonators are used in electronic circuits to generate signals of a precise frequency.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] For example, piezoelectric resonators, commonly made from quartz, are used as frequency references.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Common designs consist of electrodes attached to a piece of quartz, in the shape of a rectangular plate for high frequency applications, or in the shape of a tuning fork for low frequency applications.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The high dimensional stability and low temperature coefficient of quartz helps keeps resonant frequency constant.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In addition, the quartz's piezoelectric property converts the mechanical vibrations into an oscillating voltage, which is picked up by the attached electrodes.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] These crystal oscillators are used in quartz clocks and watches, to create the clock signal that runs computers, and to stabilize the output signal from radio transmitters.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Mechanical resonators can also be used to induce a standing wave in other media.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] For example, a multiple degree of freedom system can be created by imposing a base excitation on a cantilever beam.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In this case the standing wave is imposed on the beam.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] This type of system can be used as a sensor to track changes in frequency or phase of the resonance of the fiber.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] One application is as a measurement device for dimensional metrology.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The most familiar examples of acoustic resonators are in musical instruments.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Every musical instrument has resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Some generate the sound directly, such as the wooden bars in a xylophone, the head of a drum, the strings in stringed instruments, and the pipes in an organ.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Some modify the sound by enhancing particular frequencies, such as the sound box of a guitar or violin.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Organ pipes, the bodies of woodwinds, and the sound boxes of stringed instruments are examples of acoustic cavity resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The exhaust pipes in automobile exhaust systems are designed as acoustic resonators that work with the muffler to reduce noise, by making sound waves "cancel each other out".
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The "exhaust note" is an important feature for some vehicle owners, so both the original manufacturers and the after-market suppliers use the resonator to enhance the sound.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In "tuned exhaust" systems designed for performance, the resonance of the exhaust pipes can also be used to remove combustion products from the combustion chamber at a particular engine speed or range of speeds.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In many keyboard percussion instruments, below the centre of each note is a tube, which is an acoustic cavity resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The length of the tube varies according to the pitch of the note, with higher notes having shorter resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The tube is open at the top end and closed at the bottom end, creating a column of air that resonates when the note is struck.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] In string instruments, the body of the instrument is a resonator.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The tremolo effect of a vibraphone is achieved via a mechanism that opens and shuts the resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] String instruments such as the bluegrass banjo may also have resonators.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] Many five-string banjos have removable resonators, so players can use the instrument with a resonator in bluegrass style, or without it in folk music style.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The term *resonator*, used by itself, may also refer to the resonator guitar.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The modern ten-string guitar, invented by Narciso Yepes, adds four sympathetic string resonators to the traditional classical guitar.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] By tuning these resonators in a very specific way (C, B♭, A♭, G♭) and making use of their strongest partials (corresponding to the octaves and fifths of the strings' fundamental tones), the bass strings of the guitar now resonate equally with any of the 12 tones of the chromatic octave.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] The guitar resonator is a device for driving guitar string harmonics by an electromagnetic field.
[src:cavity-resonators/resonator] This resonance effect is caused by a feedback loop and is applied to drive the fundamental tones, octaves, 5th, 3rd to an infinite sustain.
